Supervised Learning: Regression

Project #2

Craig Drummond

Context

There is a huge demand for used cars in the Indian Market today. As sales of new cars have slowed down in the recent past, the pre-owned car market has continued to grow over the past years and is larger than the new car market now. Cars4U is a budding tech start-up that aims to find footholes in this market.

In 2018-19, while new car sales were recorded at 3.6 million units, around 4 million second-hand cars were bought and sold. There is a slowdown in new car sales and that could mean that the demand is shifting towards the pre-owned market. In fact, some car sellers replace their old cars with pre-owned cars instead of buying new ones. Unlike new cars, where price and supply are fairly deterministic and managed by OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturer / except for dealership level discounts which come into play only in the last stage of the customer journey), used cars are very different beasts with huge uncertainty in both pricing and supply. Keeping this in mind, the pricing scheme of these used cars becomes important in order to grow in the market.

As a senior data scientist at Cars4U, you have to come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing. For example, if the business knows the market price, it will never sell anything below it.

Objective

To explore and visualize the dataset, build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars, and generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.

Data Dictionary

  • S.No.: Serial number
  • Name: Name of the car which includes brand name and model name
  • Location: Location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (cities)
  • Year: Manufacturing year of the car
  • Kilometers_driven: The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in km
  • Fuel_Type: The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
  • Transmission: The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic/Manual)
  • Owner: Type of ownership
  • Mileage: The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
  • Engine: The displacement volume of the engine in CC
  • Power: The maximum power of the engine in bhp
  • Seats: The number of seats in the car
  • New_Price: The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh INR = 100,000 INR)
  • Price: The price of the used car in INR Lakhs

Key Questions

  • Which variables have the larges effect on the price of used cars
  • Does the brand name have a measurable affect on the price of used cars
  • Does the location where the care is sold have an affect on the price
  • What other factors have an effect on the price of used cars
    • Kilometers per liter
    • Horsepower
    • Passenger Capacity
    • Gas vs. Diesel

def log_trans(df, col_log):
    """Perform Log Transformation of dataframe, and a list of columns"""
    for columnName in col_log:
        df[columnName + '_log'] = np.log(df[columnName])
    df.info()

def encode_cat_variables(x):
    x = pd.get_dummies(x, columns=x.select_dtypes(include=["object", "category"]).columns.tolist(), drop_first=True)
    return x

def build_ols_model(train):
    # Create the model
    olsmodel = sm.OLS(y_train["Price_log"], train)

In [6]:
def rmse(predictions, targets):
    return np.sqrt(((targets - predictions) **2).mean())
In [7]:
def mape(predictions, targets):
    return np.mean(np.abs((targets - predictions)) / targets) * 100
In [8]:
def mae(predictions, targets):
    return np.mean(np.abs((targets - predictions)))
In [9]:
# Model Performance on both test and train data
def model_perf(olsmodel, x_train, x_test):

    # Sample Prediction
    y_pred_train_pricelog = olsmodel.predict(x_train)
    y_pred_train_Price = y_pred_train_pricelog.apply(math.exp)
    y_train_Price = y_train["Price"]
    
    # Prediction on test
    y_pred_test_pricelog = olsmodel.predict(x_test)
    y_pred_test_Price = y_pred_test_pricelog.apply(math.exp)
    y_test_Price = y_test["Price"]
    
    print(pd.DataFrame({ "Data": ["Train", "Test"],
                      "RMSE": [
                                  rmse(y_pred_train_Price, y_train_Price),
                                  rmse(y_pred_test_Price, y_test_Price),
                              ],
                      "MAE": [
                                  mae(y_pred_train_Price, y_train_Price),
                                  mae(y_pred_test_Price, y_test_Price),
                             ],
                      "MAPE": [
                                  mape(y_pred_train_Price, y_train_Price),
                                  mape(y_pred_test_Price, y_test_Price),
                      ],}))

Processing Mileage, Engine, and Power¶

In [19]:
# Clean up data that has units (need only the numberical component

# Mileage - Remove the kmpl and km/g from the end
data["Mileage"] = data["Mileage"].str.rstrip(" kmpl")
data["Mileage"] = data["Mileage"].str.rstrip(" km/g")

# Engine - Remove the CC from the end
data["Engine"] = data["Engine"].str.rstrip(" CC")

# Power - Remove bhp from the end and then replace all "null" values with np.nan
data["Power"] = data["Power"].str.rstrip(" bhp")
data["Power"] = data["Power"].replace(regex="null", value = np.nan)

# Create a new list of the columns that were cleaned up for use later
validate=['Engine', 'Power', 'Mileage']

Calculate Age of the vehicle¶

The year of the vehicle can not be used directly to determine its current age. Two new columns will be added to the data frame. The first just a temporary currentYear, all of these will be 2022. The second will be ageOfCar which will be calculated as currentYear - Year. Once this is done, the currentYear column will be dropped as it has no value for additional anaysis

In [40]:
data["currentYear"]=2020
data['ageOfCar']=data['currentYear']-data['Year']
data.drop('currentYear', axis=1, inplace=True)

# Generate countplots for all the categorical columns to visualize the categories
category_columns=['Location', 'Fuel_Type', 'Transmission', 'Owner_Type', 'brand']
plt.figure(figsize=(20,25))

for i, variable in enumerate(category_columns):
    plt.subplot(4,2,i+1)
    order = data[variable].value_counts(ascending=False).index
    ax=sns.countplot(data=data, x=data[variable], order=order, palette='viridis')
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100*p.get_height()/len(data[variable]))
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
        plt.annotate(percentage, (x,y), ha='center')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.title(variable)

Observations¶

  • ~13% of the cars sold where in Mumbai
  • ~53% of the cars sold used diesel fuel. ~45.8% used petrol, and all other methods add up to only ~1.2%
  • ~71.7% of cars sold had a manual transmission
  • ~82% of cars sold were sold by their first owner
  • ~20% of the cars sold were made by Maruti

Observations¶

  • The less a care is drive the higher the price but ther is an outlier with many more miles that still has a high relatively high price
  • Higher mileage cars cost the least
  • The more powerful the engine the higher the price, but there are outliers around 3000CC that command the highest price even though they are not the most powerful engine
  • The most expensive cars are two and 5 seaters.

Observations¶

  • Engine and Power are strongly correlated (as might be expected) (.86)
  • Mileage has a negative correlation to Engine, Power, Price and ageOfCar
  • Price has a positive correlation to Engine, Power, Seats, & New_Price (the more expenive a car is new the more likely that it will be more expesive being sold used
  • Kilometers_Driven is the least correlated to price (-0.011)
